The President of the United States and the Prime Minister of the Czech Republic met to discuss strengthening their bilateral relationship and increasing cooperation in various areas. They agreed to focus on security cooperation, economic and commercial ties (including civil nuclear energy cooperation), and promoting democracy, open government, and human rights globally. They set goals to negotiate a defense procurement agreement, establish a center for civil nuclear cooperation, and cooperate in implementing the Open Government Partnership Initiative. They also discussed the global economic situation, energy security, and the importance of nuclear power in reducing carbon emissions. They reviewed their cooperation in eastern Afghanistan and the upcoming NATO summit in Chicago, emphasizing the need for efficient use of defense resources. Lastly, they discussed supporting the transition in the Middle East and North Africa and promoting democracy and human rights, with the Czech Republic serving as an example.